HEADWORD: Homiletical
<hw>Hom`i*let"ic*al</hw>
<pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/: cf. F.
<ets>homil⟦eacute⟧tique</ets>. See <er>Homily</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Of or pertaining to familiar intercourse; social; affable;
conversable; companionable.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His virtues active, chiefly, and <qex>homiletical</qex>, not those
lazy, sullen ones of the cloister.</q>
<rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to homiletics; hortatory.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Homiletics</ent>⟦br⟧
